{"title_page": "Nuns of the Battlefield", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = Nuns of the Battlefield bas relief.jpg\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         = 300px\n| title              = Nuns of the Battlefield\n| alt                = \n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      = \n| artist             = Jerome Connor\n| year               = {{Start date|1924}} \n| type               = [[Bronze]]\n| height_metric      = 182.88\n| width_metric       = 274.32\n| length_metric      = \n| height_imperial    = \n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| metric_unit        = cm\n| imperial_unit      = in\n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n| museum             = \n| owner              = National Park Service\n{{Infobox NRHP \n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type            = cp | nocat = yes\n  | partof               = [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC]].\n  | partof_refnum        = \n  | address = \n  | location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n  | coordinates  = {{coord|38|54|20.83|N|77|2|24.89|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Washington, D.C.\n  | added = September 20, 1978 <ref name=inventory>{{cite web|url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov/natregsearchresult.do?fullresult=true&recordid=7| title = Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC| date = September 20, 1978 | publisher =National Park Service | accessdate = August 10, 2011 }}</ref>\n  | governing_body = [[National Park Service]]\n  | refnum = 78000257<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n}}\n\n'''''Nuns of the Battlefield''''' is a public artwork made in 1924 by [[Irish people|Irish]] artist [[Jerome Connor]], located at the intersection of [[Rhode Island Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Rhode Island Avenue NW]], [[M Street (Washington, D.C.)|M Street]], and [[Connecticut Avenue|Connecticut Avenue NW]], in [[Washington, D.C.]], United States. A tribute to the more than 600 nuns who nursed soldiers of both armies during the [[American Civil War]], it is one of two monuments in the District that mark women's roles in the conflict.<ref name=\"SOS\">{{cite web | author=Save Outdoor Sculpture! | year=1993 | title=Nuns of the Battlefield, (sculpture)  | work=SOS! | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!16187~!0#focus | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Testament\">Jacob, Kathryn Allmong. ''Testament to Union: Civil War monuments in Washington, Part 3''. JHU Press, 1998, p. 125-126.</ref> It is a contributing monument to the [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC|Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.]], listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]]. In 1993, it was surveyed for the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] program.\n\n==Description==\nThe face of the sculpture has a large bronze [[bas relief]] panel showing 12 nuns dressed in [[religious habit|traditional habit]]. This panel is installed on a rectangular [[granite]] slab that sits on a granite base. Each end of the slab has a bronze female figure seated. The proper right-side figure has wings, a helmet, robes, and armor to look like an [[angel]], representing  [[patriotism]]. Sitting, she holds a shield in her proper left hand and a scroll in her lap with her proper right hand. She is weaponless, to represent peace. On the proper left side of the slab, another winged figure sits wearing a long dress, a bodice, and a scarf around her head to represent the angel of [[Peace]]. Her hands are folded on her lap.\n\nThe lower right side of the relief is signed: JEROME CONNOR 1924\n\nThe lower left side of the relief is inscribed:\n\n:[[Bureau Brothers Foundry|BUREAU BROS.]]\n:BRONZE FOUNDERS PHILA\n:ENN\n\nOn the granite above the relief is inscribed:\n\n:THEY COMFORTED THE DYING, NURSED THE WOUNDED, CARRIED HOPE TO\n:THE IMPRISONED, GAVE IN HIS NAME A DRINK OF WATER TO THE THIRSTY.\n\nOn the granite below the relief:\n\n:TO THE MEMORY AND IN HONOR OF\n:THE VARIOUS ORDERS OF SISTERS\n:WHO GAVE THEIR SERVICES AS NURSES ON BATTLEFIELDS\n:AND IN HOSPITALS DURING THE CIVIL WAR.\n\nOn the rear of the slab near the base is inscribed:\n\n:ERECTED BY THE LADIES AUXILIARY TO THE ANCIENT ORDER OF HIBERNIANS OF AMERICA. A.D. 1924\n:BY AUTHORITY OF THE CONGRESS OF THE UNITED STATES.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==Artist==\n\nBorn in Ireland in 1874, Jerome Connor moved at the age of 14 with his family to [[Massachusetts]]. His father was a [[stonemason]], which led to Connor's jobs in New York as a sign painter, stonecutter, bronze founder, and machinist. Inspired by his father's work and his own experience, Connor used to steal his father's chisels as a child and carve figures into rocks.\n\nIn 1899, he moved into the [[Roycroft Institution]] where he helped with [[blacksmithing]] and eventually began making [[terracotta]] busts and reliefs. During four years at Roycroft, he became well known as a sculptor, and was commissioned to create civic works in bronze for placement in Washington, D.C., [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[East Aurora, New York]], San Francisco, and Ireland.\n\nIn 1925, he moved back to Ireland and opened his own studio in [[Dublin]], but found few patrons and his work slowed. He died on August 21, 1943, of heart failure.<ref name=\"Annascual\">{{cite web | author= | year= | title=Jerome Connor 1874\u20131943 Sculptor | work=Jerome Connor | publisher=Annascual | url=http://www.annascaul.net/jerome_connor_sculptor.php | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref> There is a plaque in his honour on Infirmary Road, overlooking Dublin's [[Phoenix Park]], with the words of his friend the poet [[Patrick Kavanagh]]:\n\n:He sits in a corner of my memory\n:With his short pipe, holding it by the bowl,\n:And his sharp eye and his knotty fingers\n:And his laughing soul\n:Shining through the gaps of his crusty wall.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\n==History==\n\nThe idea for the monument originated with Ellen Jolly, president of the women's auxiliary branch of the [[Ancient Order of Hibernians]] who grew up hearing stories of battlefield tales told by nuns. Proposing the sculpture just after the turn of the century, her request was denied by the War Department until proof of service was provided. For ten years Jolly worked to gather evidence and presented it to Congress in 1918.<ref name=\"Testament\"/>\n\nThe sculpture was authorized by [[United States Congress|Congress]] on March 29, 1918 with the agreement that the government would not fund it. A committee, led by Jolly, on behalf of the Ancient Order of the Hibernians, raised $50,000 for the project.<ref name=\"SOS\"/><ref name=\"Testament\"/>\n\nJerome Connor was chosen since he focused on Irish Catholic themes, being one himself.<ref name=\"Testament\"/>\n\n==Acquisition==\n\nA construction delay was caused due to the final location of the sculpture. [[Jerome Connor]] wanted the sculpture either at [[Arlington National Cemetery]] or at the [[Pan American Union Building]]. Neither choice was supported by the War Department or the DC Fine Arts Commission and the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]] decided on the final location near [[Dupont Circle]]. Once the location was chosen, the Arts Commission requested that the sculpture be changed by Connor. They requested that he alter the size, move inscriptions on the front, rearrange the front steps and make the angels \"active.\" A year later, in 1919, Congress finally approved of the design.<ref name=\"Testament\"/> Construction began on July 28, 1924.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nFinally, [[Jerome Connor]] ended up suing the Ancient Order of the Hibernians for nonpayment.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nThe monument was dedicated on September 20, 1924 as part of a weekend long meeting of over 5,000 Catholics from all over the country. One nun, Sister Magdeline of the Sisters of Mercy, who served in the Civil War attended the event and was received with a \"thunderous applause.\" [[William Henry O'Connell|Archbishop O'Connell]] of Boston spoke and upon finishing, Jolly revealed the sculpture by removing an [[American flag]] that covered it. Sailors hoisted signal flags spelling \"faith, hope and charity\" and a flock of white [[pigeons]] were released.<ref name=\"Testament\"/><ref name=\"CatholicDC\">{{cite web | author=John W. Tuohy | year= | title=Nuns of the Battlefield | work=When Washington Was Irish | publisher= | url=http://whenwashingtonwasirish.blogspot.com/2010/10/nuns-of-battlefield.html | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Information==\n\nThe nuns represented on the relief are from the [[Sisters of St. Joseph]], [[Carmelites]], [[Dominican Order]], [[Ursulines]], [[Sisters of the Holy Cross]], [[Poor Sisters of St. Francis]], [[Sisters of Mercy]], [[Congregation of the Sisters of Our Lady of Mercy]], [[Daughters of Charity of St. Vincent de Paul]], [[Sisters of Charity of Nazareth]], [[Sisters of Providence of Saint Mary-of-the-Woods]], and [[Congregation of Divine Providence]].<ref name=\"HMDB\">{{cite web | author=Craig Swain | year=2008 | title=Nuns of the Battlefield | work=Northwest in Washington, District of Columbia \u2014 The American Northeast (Mid-Atlantic) | publisher=The Historical Marker Database | url=http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=10176 | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* J. Goode, ''Washington Sculpture'', The Johns Hopkins University Press, 2008. {{ISBN|0-8018-8810-7}}, A cultural history of outdoor sculpture in the Nation's capital.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0001660.htm ''Nuns of the Battlefield'' on DCMemorials]\n*[http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/23403 Roadside America]\n\n{{Washington DC landmarks}}\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n[[Category:Irish art]]\n[[Category:Irish-American culture in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1924 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to women]]\n[[Category:Nursing monuments and memorials]]\n[[Category:Women in the American Civil War|+]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic religious sisters and nuns|+]]\n[[Category:Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of women in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = Nuns of the Battlefield bas relief.jpg\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         = 300px\n| title              = Nuns of the Battlefield\n| alt                = \n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      = \n| artist             = Jerome Connor\n| year               = {{Start date|1924}} \n| type               = [[Bronze]]\n| height_metric      = 182.88\n| width_metric       = 274.32\n| length_metric      = \n| height_imperial    = \n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| metric_unit        = cm\n| imperial_unit      = in\n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n| museum             = \n| owner              = National Park Service\n{{Infobox NRHP \n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type            = cp | nocat = yes\n  | partof               = [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC]].\n  | partof_refnum        = \n  | address = \n  | location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n  | coordinates  = {{coord|38|54|20.83|N|77|2|24.89|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Washington, D.C.\n  | added = September 20, 1978 <ref name=inventory>{{cite web|url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov/natregsearchresult.do?fullresult=true&recordid=7| title = Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC| date = September 20, 1978 | publisher =National Park Service | accessdate = August 10, 2011 }}</ref>\n  | governing_body = [[National Park Service]]\n  | refnum = 78000257<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n}}\n\n'''''Nuns of the Battlefield''''' is a public artwork made in 1924 by [[Irish people|Irish]] artist [[Jerome Connor]], located at the intersection of [[Rhode Island Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Rhode Island Avenue NW]], [[M Street (Washington, D.C.)|M Street]], and [[Connecticut Avenue|Connecticut Avenue NW]], in [[Washington, D.C.]], United States. A tribute to the more than 600 nuns who nursed soldiers of both armies during the [[American Civil War]], it is one of two monuments in the District that mark women's roles in the conflict.<ref name=\"SOS\">{{cite web | author=Save Outdoor Sculpture! | year=1993 | title=Nuns of the Battlefield, (sculpture)  | work=SOS! | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!16187~!0#focus | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Testament\">Jacob, Kathryn Allmong. ''Testament to Union: Civil War monuments in Washington, Part 3''. JHU Press, 1998, p. 125-126.</ref> It is a contributing monument to the [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC|Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.]], listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]]. In 1993, it was surveyed for the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] program.\n\n==Description==\nThe face of the sculpture has a large bronze [[bas relief]] panel showing 12 nuns dressed in [[religious habit|traditional habit]]. This panel is installed on a rectangular [[granite]] slab that sits on a granite base. Each end of the slab has a bronze female figure seated. The proper right-side figure has wings, a helmet, robes, and armor to look like an [[angel]], representing  [[patriotism]]. Sitting, she holds a shield in her proper left hand and a scroll in her lap with her proper right hand. She is weaponless, to represent peace. On the proper left side of the slab, another winged figure sits wearing a long dress, a bodice, and a scarf around her head to represent the angel of [[Peace]]. Her hands are folded on her lap.\n\nThe lower right side of the relief is signed: JEROME CONNOR 1924\n\nThe lower left side of the relief is inscribed:\n\n:[[Bureau Brothers Foundry|BUREAU BROS.]]\n:BRONZE FOUNDERS PHILA\n:ENN\n\nOn the granite above the relief is inscribed:\n\n:THEY COMFORTED THE DYING, NURSED THE WOUNDED, CARRIED HOPE TO\n:THE IMPRISONED, GAVE IN HIS NAME A DRINK OF WATER TO THE THIRSTY.\n\nOn the granite below the relief:\n\n:TO THE MEMORY AND IN HONOR OF\n:THE VARIOUS ORDERS OF SISTERS\n:WHO GAVE THEIR SERVICES AS NURSES ON BATTLEFIELDS\n:AND IN HOSPITALS DURING THE CIVIL WAR.\n\nOn the rear of the slab near the base is inscribed:\n\n:ERECTED BY THE LADIES AUXILIARY TO THE ANCIENT ORDER OF HIBERNIANS OF AMERICA. A.D. 1924\n:BY AUTHORITY OF THE CONGRESS OF THE UNITED STATES.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==Artist==\n\nBorn in Ireland in 1874, Jerome Connor moved at the age of 14 with his family to [[Massachusetts]]. His father was a [[stonemason]], which led to Connor's jobs in New York as a sign painter, stonecutter, bronze founder, and machinist. Inspired by his father's work and his own experience, Connor used to steal his father's chisels as a child and carve figures into rocks.\n\nIn 1899, he moved into the [[Roycroft Institution]] where he helped with [[blacksmithing]] and eventually began making [[terracotta]] busts and reliefs. During four years at Roycroft, he became well known as a sculptor, and was commissioned to create civic works in bronze for placement in Washington, D.C., [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[East Aurora, New York]], San Francisco, and Ireland.\n\nIn 1925, he moved back to Ireland and opened his own studio in [[Dublin]], but found few patrons and his work slowed. He died on August 21, 1943, of heart failure.<ref name=\"Annascual\">{{cite web | author= | year= | title=Jerome Connor 1874\u20131943 Sculptor | work=Jerome Connor | publisher=Annascual | url=http://www.annascaul.net/jerome_connor_sculptor.php | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref> There is a plaque in his honour on Infirmary Road, overlooking Dublin's [[Phoenix Park]], with the words of his friend the poet [[Patrick Kavanagh]]:\n\n:He sits in a corner of my memory\n:With his short pipe, holding it by the bowl,\n:And his sharp eye and his knotty fingers\n:And his laughing soul\n:Shining through the gaps of his crusty wall.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\n==History==\n\nThe idea for the monument originated with Ellen Jolly, president of the women's auxiliary branch of the [[Ancient Order of Hibernians]] who grew up hearing stories of battlefield tales told by nuns. Proposing the sculpture just after the turn of the century, her request was denied by the War Department until proof of service was provided. For ten years Jolly worked to gather evidence and presented it to Congress in 1918.<ref name=\"Testament\"/>\n\nThe sculpture was authorized by [[United States Congress|Congress]] on March 29, 1918 with the agreement that the government would not fund it. A committee, led by Jolly, on behalf of the Ancient Order of the Hibernians, raised $50,000 for the project.<ref name=\"SOS\"/><ref name=\"Testament\"/>\n\nJerome Connor was chosen since he focused on Irish Catholic themes, being one himself.<ref name=\"Testament\"/>\n\n==Acquisition==\n\nA construction delay was caused due to the final location of the sculpture. [[Jerome Connor]] wanted the sculpture either at [[Arlington National Cemetery]] or at the [[Pan American Union Building]]. Neither choice was supported by the War Department or the DC Fine Arts Commission and the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]] decided on the final location near [[Dupont Circle]]. Once the location was chosen, the Arts Commission requested that the sculpture be changed by Connor. They requested that he alter the size, move inscriptions on the front, rearrange the front steps and make the angels \"active.\" A year later, in 1919, Congress finally approved of the design.<ref name=\"Testament\"/> Construction began on July 28, 1924.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nFinally, [[Jerome Connor]] ended up suing the Ancient Order of the Hibernians for nonpayment.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nThe monument was dedicated on September 20, 1924 as part of a weekend long meeting of over 5,000 Catholics from all over the country. One nun, Sister Magdeline of the Sisters of Mercy, who served in the Civil War attended the event and was received with a \"thunderous applause.\" [[William Henry O'Connell|Archbishop O'Connell]] of Boston spoke and upon finishing, Jolly revealed the sculpture by removing an [[American flag]] that covered it. Sailors hoisted signal flags spelling \"faith, hope and charity\" and a flock of white [[pigeons]] were released.<ref name=\"Testament\"/><ref name=\"CatholicDC\">{{cite web | author=John W. Tuohy | year= | title=Nuns of the Battlefield | work=When Washington Was Irish | publisher= | url=http://whenwashingtonwasirish.blogspot.com/2010/10/nuns-of-battlefield.html | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Information==\n\nThe nuns represented on the relief are from the [[Sisters of St. Joseph]], [[Carmelites]], [[Dominican Order]], [[Ursulines]], [[Sisters of the Holy Cross]], [[Poor Sisters of St. Francis]], [[Sisters of Mercy]], [[Congregation of the Sisters of Our Lady of Mercy]], [[Daughters of Charity of St. Vincent de Paul]], [[Sisters of Charity of Nazareth]], [[Sisters of Providence of Saint Mary-of-the-Woods]], and [[Congregation of Divine Providence]].<ref name=\"HMDB\">{{cite web | author=Craig Swain | year=2008 | title=Nuns of the Battlefield | work=Northwest in Washington, District of Columbia \u2014 The American Northeast (Mid-Atlantic) | publisher=The Historical Marker Database | url=http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=10176 | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* J. Goode, ''Washington Sculpture'', The Johns Hopkins University Press, 2008. {{ISBN|0-8018-8810-7}}, A cultural history of outdoor sculpture in the Nation's capital.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Nuns of the Battlefield Memorial, Washington, D.C.}}\n*[http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0001660.htm ''Nuns of the Battlefield'' on DCMemorials]\n*[http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/23403 Roadside America]\n\n{{Washington DC landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Irish art]]\n[[Category:Irish-American culture in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1924 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to women]]\n[[Category:Nursing monuments and memorials]]\n[[Category:Women in the American Civil War|+]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic religious sisters and nuns|+]]\n[[Category:Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of women in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "+Template:Public art in Washington, D.C.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuns_of_the_Battlefield"}
{"title_page": "Nazad, nazad, Kalino mome", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Nazad, nazad, Kalino mome''''' ({{lang-bg|\u041d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043c\u043e\u043c\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e}}, {{lang-mk|\u041d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e \u043c\u043e\u043c\u0435}}, {{lang-en|Go back, go back, girl Kalina}}) is a traditional [[Bulgaria]]n <ref>[http://www.pe-bg.com/?cid=3&pid=27250&cat=145 \u041d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043c\u043e\u043c\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e, \u0410\u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438 \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438, \u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b: BalkaNota, \u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430: 2008], {{ISBN|9790707680209}}</ref> and [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonian]] [[folk song]]. It's in the time signature of 7/8.<ref>http://www.myspace.com/balkanyspiewaja</ref> The song was performed by the Swedish pop group [[Ace of Base]] during their concert in [[Lovech]], Bulgaria in May 2008.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.bulphoto.com/events/12643/\n|title=\"Ace of Base\" performed  \"Nazad, nazad Kalino mome\" in Lovech\n|publisher=www.bulphoto.com\n|accessdate=2009-05-03\n|last=\n|first=\n|language=bg}}\n</ref> Other famous performers include [[Jovan Jovanov]], Aleksandra Pileva, [[Slavi Trifonov]], [[Nevena Tsoneva]] and [[Gloria (Bulgarian singer)|Gloria]] among others.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.slavishow.com/index.php?cat=6&mid=41&id=7738\n|title=\"Nazad, nazad Kalino mome\" on the concert in Burgas\n|publisher=www.slavishow.com\n|accessdate=2009-05-03\n|last=\n|first=\n|language=bg}}\n</ref> The norwegian composer [[Thomas Bergersen|Thomas J. Bergersen]] has featured part of the lyrics in his song \"Never give up on your dreams\", from the album ''[[Unleashed (Two Steps from Hell album)|Unleashed]]'', of the company Two Steps from Hell. He has composed other songs in the Bulgarian language, such as \"Colors of Love\", \"Fearless\", \"Rada\" or \"Starvation\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/TwoStepsFromHell/comments/7hbs9o/never_give_up_on_your_dreams_lyrics/?st=jk86eve7&sh=71287abe|title=r/TwoStepsFromHell - Never Give Up On Your Dreams - Lyrics|website=reddit|language=en|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.balkanfolk.com/bg/lyrics.php?lyrics_id=961\n|title=Lyrics of the song in Bulgarian\n|publisher=www.balkanfolk.com\n|accessdate=2009-05-03\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n\n*[http://pesna.org/song.asp?id=62 The lyrics in Macedonian with transliteration]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pg2mhunskgI Nazad Nazad Kalino mome performed by Suzana Spasovska]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V17ij5Ap1pA Reinterpretation by Thomas Bergersen]\n\n{{Macedonian Folk Songs}}\n\n[[Category:Bulgarian folk songs]]\n[[Category:Macedonian folk songs]]\n\n\n{{Folk-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Nazad, nazad, Kalino mome''''' ({{lang-bg|\u041d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043c\u043e\u043c\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e}}, {{lang-mk|\u041d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e \u043c\u043e\u043c\u0435}}, {{lang-en|Go back, go back, girl Kalina}}) is a traditional [[Bulgaria]]n <ref>[http://www.pe-bg.com/?cid=3&pid=27250&cat=145 \u041d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0434, \u043c\u043e\u043c\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e, ISBN: 9790707680209, \u0410\u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438 \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438, \u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b: BalkaNota, \u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430: 2008]</ref> and [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonian]] [[folk song]]. It's in th