xo Supercube Motorsport]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} John Giddings<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} Bruce Stewart\n| [[Ford Sierra RS500]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 82\n|- \n! NC\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 28\n| Capri Components\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} Lawrie Nelson<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} Bob Jolly\n| [[Ford Mustang (third generation)#1983\u20131986|Ford Mustang]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 78\n|- \n! DNF\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n| CANAM Enterprises\n| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Graeme Crosby]]<br>{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Graham McRae]]\n| [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 74\n|- \n! DNF\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 42\n| Jagparts Racing\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} Gerald Kay<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} Alf Grant\n| [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 73\n|- \n! NC\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| B\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 10\n| [[Phil Ward Racing|Reithmuller-Ward Int. Motorsport]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} Phil Ward<br>{{flagicon|FRG}} Llynden Reithmuller<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} Chris Clearihan\n| [[Mercedes-Benz W201#190 E 2.3-16 & 2.5-16 \"Cosworth\"|Mercedes-Benz 190E 190 E 2.3-16]] <ref name=Program/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 55\n|- \n! DNF\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 45\n| L Smerdon\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} Lester Smerdon<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} Bruce Willams\n| [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 43\n|- \n! DNF\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 12  <ref name=touringcarracing.net/>\n| RG Lanyon\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Peter McLeod]]<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Peter Fitzgerald (racing driver)|Peter Fitzgerald]]\n| [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 17\n|- \n! DNF\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n| Bob Jane T-Marts\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Allan Grice]]<br>{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Win Percy]]\n| [[Holden VL Commodore SS Group A]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 10\n|- \n! DNF\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 27\n| Sunliner \n| {{flagicon|AUS}} Tony Hunter<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} Warren McKellar\n| [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|- \n! DNS\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| B\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 17\n| Shell Ultra-Hi Tech Racing Team\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Dick Johnson (racing driver)|Dick Johnson]]<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Gregg Hansford]]\n| [[Ford Sierra RS500]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|- \n! DNS\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| B\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 35\n| [[Miedecke Motorsport|Oxo Supercube Motorsport]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Andrew Miedecke]]<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Don Smith (racing driver)|Don Smith]]\n| [[Ford Sierra RS500]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|}\n\n==Statistics==\n* Pole Position \u2013 #17 Dick Johnson - [[Ford Sierra RS500]] \u2013 1:47.59\n* Fastest Lap \u2013 #18 Dick Johnson - Ford Sierra RS500 \u2013 1:50.28 (new lap record) <ref name=Naismith/>\n* Race time of winning car - 4:10:28.06 <ref name=Tuckey/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1987 Australian Touring Car season]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080721014717/http://www.groupc.org.au/Photo%20Gallery/Archives_Group_A/index.htm Group A Archives (including 1987 Castrol 500 images), www.groupc.org.au as archived at web.archive.org] \n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m7T0WZGc7hA 1987 Castrol 500 - full race, www.youtube.com]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Castrol 500]] | style=\"text-align:center;\"| before=[[1986 Castrol 500]] | years=1987 | after=[[1988 Enzed 500]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:Motorsport at Sandown]]\n[[Category:1987 in Australian motorsport|Castrol 500]]\n[[Category:Pre-Bathurst 500]]\n", "text_old": "The '''1987 Castrol 500''' was a race for Touring Cars complying with Appendix C of the National Competition Rules of the [[Confederation of Australian Motor Sport]] <ref name=Program>Official Program, Castrol 500, Sandown 13 September 1987, pages 36 & 37</ref> (commonly known as [[Group A Touring Cars]]). The event was staged on 13 September 1987 over 129 laps of the 3.9&nbsp;km [[Sandown Raceway|Sandown circuit]] in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]], a total distance of 503&nbsp;km.\n\nThe race, the 22nd [[Sandown 500]], was won by [[George Fury]] and Terry Shiel, driving a [[Nissan Skyline#RS|Nissan Skyline DR30 RS]].\n\n==Summary==\n[[File:Nissan Skyline RS Fury (15749239780).jpg|thumb|[[George Fury]] and Terry Shiel won the race driving a [[Nissan Skyline DR30 RS]].]]\n\n===Qualifying===\nThe race saw the Australian debut of the evolution [[Ford Sierra RS500]]. Although none of the four Sierras finished the race (two in fact did not start), the new {{Convert|470|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} model proved it would be the car to beat at [[1987 James Hardie 1000]]. Andrew Miedecke in his [[Miedecke Motorsport|Oxo Supercubes]] Sierra (an [[Andy Rouse]] kit car) attained provisional pole position in qualifying with a time of 1:49.45 before his weekend ended when co-driver Don Smith rolled the car at the end of pit straight, just prior to the end of qualifying. [[Dick Johnson (racing driver)|Dick Johnson]] went even better in the Dulux Dozen runoff for pole with a time of 1:47.59, almost two seconds quicker than Miedecke's time earlier in the day. This time would remain the fastest ever Group A touring car time recorded on the 3.9&nbsp;km long international circuit.\n\n[[Peter Brock]] attracted pre-race criticism for his decision to have [[Seven Network|Channel 7]] television commentator [[Neil Crompton]] as the lead driver of the [[Holden Dealer Team#Group A|Mobil 1]] teams second [[Holden VL Commodore SS Group A|Holden Commodore]] with accusations of it being nothing more than a [[Public relations|PR]] exercise after the bad press the team had received in 1987 in the wake of Brock's split with [[Holden]]. However, despite his relative lack of experience in touring cars, Crompton put in a credible performance and ended up in 11th place after the Dulux Dozen. With new [[Bridgestone]] tyres and an adjustable rear end developed by the team that allowed negative camber of the rear tyres transforming the handling of the Commodore, plus some extra engine development up to and following the [[Spa 24 Hours]] bringing power up to a respectable {{Convert|420|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}, Brock himself qualified fifth, only a couple of tenths behind [[Allan Grice]]'s Les Small prepared [[Roadways Racing|Roadways]] VL Commodore and some 1.5 seconds faster than [[Larry Perkins]] in the older model [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A|VK]]. Both Grice and Perkins were running engines with approximately {{Convert|40|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} more than the HDT cars.\n\n===Race===\nThe 1987 Castrol 500 was won by the [[Gibson Motor Sport|Peter Jackson Nissan Racing]] [[Nissan Skyline#RS|Skyline DR30 RS]] of [[George Fury]] and Terry Shiel. The win continued the Nissan team's winning streak at Sandown in 1986 and 1987 with the Skyline, having won the ATCC rounds at the circuit in both years as well as Fury and [[Glenn Seton]] having won the [[1986 Castrol 500]]. They won by a lap from the [[Holden V8 engine|V8]] [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A|Holden VK Commodore]] of [[Larry Perkins]] and [[Denny Hulme]] with the New Zealand Nissan Skyline of Kent Baigent and Graeme Bowkett a further lap back in third place. [[New Zealanders|Kiwi]]s Kaigent and Bowkett continued to impress with their speed in the privateer Skyline, never falling out of the top five during the race except during pit stops. The NZ Skyline was engineered by Jim and Ross Stone who would later go on to work with both [[Andrew Miedecke]] and Dick Johnson Sierra's over the next few seasons before forming their own team [[Stone Brothers Racing]]. The car also featured a lot of technical input from the Peter Jackson team.\n\nThe Ford Sierra of pole sitter Dick Johnson suffered an engine failure in the race morning warmup which forced him and [[Gregg Hansford]] to move to the teams second car. After starting from 14th on the grid, Johnson showed the speed of the new Sierra by storming to the front after just 7 laps, leaving the BMW's, Commodores and turbo Nissans in his wake on Sandown's long front and back straights. Johnson would go on to set a Group A lap record of 1:50.28 before the #18 car was retired with engine failure on lap 86.\n\nThe [[JPS Team BMW]] [[E30 M3|M3]] of [[Jim Richards (racing driver)|Jim Richards]] and [[Tony Longhurst]] held second place late in the race and Richards was contesting the lead with Fury on the now damp track due to light rain until the [[BMW S14|2.3 L engine]] lost oil pressure on lap 118. Just five laps earlier, the [[Holden VL Commodore SS Group A|Holden VL Commodore]] of [[Peter Brock]] had been holding a strong third place comfortably in front of Perkins until his front brakes suddenly gave out at the end of pit straight. Brock slid sideways into the sandtrap and was lucky not to roll the Commodore after the driver's side wheels dug into the sand.<ref name=Naismith>{{cite book|last1=Naismith|first1=Barry|title=Bathurst 1987/88|date=December 1987|publisher=Garry Sparke & Associates|location=Glen Waverley, Victoria|isbn=0 908 081 359|pages=60\u201371 The Castrol 500: The Match Race|edition=First}}</ref>\n\nThe Up to 2000cc class was won by the Peter Jackson Nissan [[Nissan Gazelle|Gazelle]] of young gun [[Mark Skaife]] and part-time [[Group B Sports Sedans|sports sedan]] racer Grant Jarrett from the [[Toyota Team Australia]] [[Toyota Corolla (E90)|Corolla]] of Mike Quinn and [[John Faulkner (racing driver)|John Faulkner]] and the [[Toyota AE86|Toyota Sprinter]] of Sydney veterans [[Bob Holden (racing driver)|Bob Holden]] and Garry Willmington.\n\n===Television coverage===\nAustralian broadcasters Channel Seven covered both the Saturday shootout and the entire race. A copy can be found online at: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m7T0WZGc7hA\n\n==Classes==\nCars competed in three engine capacity classes:<ref name=Program/>\n* Class A: 3001 cc - 6000 cc <ref name=Program/>\n* Class B: 2001 cc - 3000 cc <ref name=Program/>\n* Class C: Up to 2000 cc <ref name=Program/>\n\n==Results==\n\n===Dulux Dozen===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n! Pos\n! No\n! Team\n! Driver\n! Car\n! Time\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold\"\n! Pole\n| 17\n| [[Dick Johnson Racing|Shell Ultra-Hi Tech Racing Team]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Dick Johnson (racing driver)|Dick Johnson]]\n| [[Ford Sierra RS500]]\n| 1:47.59\n|-\n! 2\n| 1\n| [[JPS Team BMW]]\n| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Jim Richards (race driver)|Jim Richards]]\n| [[E30 M3|BMW M3]]\n| 1:48.43\n|-\n! 3\n| 30\n| [[Gibson Motor Sport|Peter Jackson Nissan Racing]]\n| {{flagicon|Australia}} [[George Fury]]\n| [[Nissan Skyline#RS|Nissan Skyline DR30 RS]]\n| 1:49.43\n|-\n! 4\n| 2\n| [[Roadways Racing]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Allan Grice]]\n| [[Holden VL Commodore SS Group A]]\n| 1:49.63\n|-\n! 5\n| 05\n| [[Holden Dealer Team|HDT Racing P/L]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Peter Brock]]\n| [[Holden VL Commodore SS Group A]]\n| 1:49.81\n|-\n! 6\n| 25\n| Team Nissan Racing NZ\n| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Graeme Bowkett]]\n| [[Nissan Skyline DR30 RS]]\n| 1:50.01\n|-\n! 7\n| 3\n| JPS Team BMW\n| {{flagicon|FRG}} [[Ludwig Finauer]]\n| [[E30 M3|BMW M3]]\n| 1:51.14\n|-\n! 8\n| 15\n| Peter Jackson Nissan Racing\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Glenn Seton]]\n| [[Nissan Skyline DR30 RS]]\n| 1:51.18\n|-\n! 9\n| 11\n| [[Perkins Engineering|Enzed Team Perkins]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Larry Perkins]]\n| [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]]\n| 1:51.31\n|-\n! 10\n| 14\n| NetComm (Aust)\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Murray Carter]] <ref name=Tuckey>Elisabeth Tuckey, Fury Disproves the Knockers, Racing Cars News, November 1987, pages 54\u201358</ref>\n| [[Nissan Skyline DR30